                CKTSIM DEMONSTRATOR VERSION DOCUMENTATION

Purpose:

This document will give sufficient information to operate the
demonstrator version of cktsim.

Overwiew:

Cktsim is a general logic simulator, aimed at use in CMOS type circuitry,
but able to model TTL or NMOS circuitry as well. The simulation is done
at the "switch" level, meaning that the basic unit of simulation is the
transistor. It is also possible to model resistors for pull up/pull down
use, and capacitors using gate capacitience.

Input:

The input is in the form of a "net list", which is in two basic parts:

     1. Nodes. These are simply "connections", and are N-way. The real
        world equvalient is a wire, which may connect up to N-many
        devices/outputs. Each node has a unique name.

     2. Transistors. Both P and N transistors are represented.
        P transistors behave as switches that are ON when a
        negative voltage appears on the gate. N transistors are
        ON when a positive voltage appears on the gate.
        Transistors are unnamed.

The net list, then, appears as an arbitrary "net" of devices and the
connections between.
Interspersed with the net definitions, several mode commands may appear.
The net file, then, can be a complete description of the circuit,
simulated inputs, output format controls, test data, etc. In short,
the complete simulation control.

Simulation:

Once the net is entered and all commands have been executed, the simulation
is run. This consists of a series of simulated "clock ticks", in which some
unit of time is simulated. This is an arbitrary definition, and will match
reality best when the worst case delay for a transistor to switch when it's
gate value changes state.
Each clock tick represents a cycle where the simulator has gone through all
the transistors in the circuit sequentailly, evaluating what the next state
of every device will be from the last state. In this way, the paralell working
of true hardware is simulated.

Output:

Two basic modes of output may be specified: list and timing chart. In list
mode, each signal to be listed is given a collumn, and as many signals as
will fit onto a line will be printed. Each line represents a clock tick.
In timing chart mode, Each signal occupies a line, and each collumn represents
a clock tick. In addition, the signal states are filtered in this mode
to look like logic analizer traces. Which type of presentation is chosen
is simply a matter of taste.
The output can be left "plain", usually for presentation on a CRT, or can
be pagenated, with headers, page numbers and margins suitable for printout.

General use mode:

Used simply as a transistor level simulator, cktsim is an IC level design
tool. Small nets of transistors may be modeled into the typical gates used.
All the tools of CMOS IC design are present, including weak transistors
for pullup and other uses.
Beyond this, a macro system is avalible. The usual first level which
such macros form are gates such as nand, nor, invert, the CMOS transmission
gate, etc. Once the simple gates are built up, the design building can
proceed using nothing but such gates if desired. Thus, in fact, the designer
can forget entirely that the basic unit of simulation is the transistor.
The levels would proceed through flip - flops, adders, etc.
Here we reach a basic branch point depending on the design purpose. With
IC design, the net can be built up with arbitrary cells, connecting gates,
and individual transistors, limited only by silicon area.
With board level design, the goal is typically to simulate standard SSI,
MSI and LSI packages (although the designer may choose to simply design
using the "obvious" functions such as gates, latches, etc., and worry
about packaging after the design is simulated). Each package, representing
a real world IC package, is defined into a macro for use. Typically, the
macro can be made avalible in a "library" of such macros, say a "74XX"
libary representing that family. In this way, the net representing the
board level design has direct correspondence to the actual board schematic.

Cktsim activation:

     cs <netfile> {option}

"cs" is the abbreviated form of cktsim. The "netfile" can be any file with
any extention. If no extention is given, ".ckt" is presumed. The implemented
options are as follows:

     #c        - Sets the output mode to "timing chart".

     #l=<file> - Sets where the output of the simulation will go.
                 Any file or device name may be specified.

Net file commands:

     p <source> <gate> <drain> - Defines a p-channel transistor.
     Each of the source, gate and drain connections is defined
     by a node name label, which is a sequence of letters or
     digits starting with a letter. The first time a node label
     appears, that node is "declared", and any subsequent appearances
     of the same name indicate connection to the same point.

     n <source> <gate> <drain> - Defines an n-channel transistor.

     wp <source> <gate> <drain> - Defines a weak p-channel transistor.
     This operates the same as a normal p transistor, but will
     "lose" in contention with a normal "strong" n or p transistor.
     Several uses include pullups, contention resolution, etc.

     wn <source> <gate> <drain> - Defines a weak n-channel transistor.

     set <node> <state> [<clock>] {<state> [<clock>]} - Defines
     a "set" sequence for a node. This is a progression of states
     to be artificially set on a node. The "clock" is the clock
     tick time in which the set is to take effect. If omitted,
     the clock value defaults to 0, or the start of the simulation.
     Any number of sets for the node may appear.
     The clock specification may appear in any of the following
     forms:

          <integer> - The number of the clock time.
          +<integer> - The current clock time plus the clock
          number specified (not really usefull in the present
          version of cktsim).
          <integer>:<integer> - This is a periodic set. The first
          number represents the clock time as above. Each time
          the set occurs, however, the second value is added
          to the current clock, meaning that it will be reset
          to happen n-clocks into the future.

     clockscale <num> - Sets the ratio of real time to simulator
     clock ticks. If the parameter is set to the average gate
     delay of the type of curcuitry being designed, the clock
     numbers appearing in printouts will be representative of
     real world time. This also affects all clock values
     appearing after in the net list. Placing it at the start of
     the net file means that all times in the net commands are
     specified in real mode. Placing it at the end means that
     all times are specified in unscaled mode. Either way,
     the printout will appear scaled.

     chart - Sets the print mode to "timing chart".

     list - Sets the print mode to "list".

     step <num>  - Sets the number of simulation clocks to perform.

     line <num> - Sets the width of the print line. The default is 79,
     appropriate for both screen and paper printouts.

     page [<num>] - Sets pagenation on. This causes headers, page
     numbers and form feeds to be generated, suitible for
     printout. If the parameter is present, this will be taken
     as the page length, which is set to a default 60, proper
     for a 66 line page.

     margin [<num>] - Set left margin on. This is usually used
     in conjunction with the line command to center the printout,
     for instance to insert the printout into a binder.
     If the parameter is present, that many left margin spaces
     will be provided, else the default is 10.

     format <node> {<node>} - Set what nodes are to be displayed.
     On a very busy net, it is usually nessary to pick out the
     relivant signals to be displayed.

     macro <name> <param> {<param>} - Define macro. All the following
     lines until the "endmac" statement are stored as the macro
     definition, to be expanded later. Any number of parameters
     may be specified. The label used is irrelivant, and serves
     as a marker for the "actual" parameter at expansion time.

     endmac - Terminates a macro definition.

     <macro> <param> {<param>} - Perform macro. Here the command
     name is the same as was defined in a preceeding macro statement.
     Macros are expanded by executing each line of the stored macro
     in the original order. Before the line is executed, it is searched
     for the parameter labels given in the original macro
     specification. When found, these are replaced with the
     "actual" parameters found in the same position in the
     macro expansion statement.
     The "@" character expands to the number of times the macro
     has been expanded, which enables the writting of unique
     node labels.
     The macro expansion must have the same number of parameters
     as the original definition.

                      NODE STATES AND THEIR DEFINITIONS

The following is a list and full explaination of the node states, their
memnonic letters, their meanings, and the results of their combination.
Where possible, a meaningfull letter has been chosen for the state. Where
this was not possible, they are lettered in 'a'-'z' fashion.

Undefined states: an undefined node may in fact have any voltage value
between vss and vcc. There are, however, many different types of undefineds,
classed roughly as "driven" and "stored".

U-Undefined               The node has never been connected to any source of
                          current, is in high - Z, and contains the
                          indeterminate state leftover from power on.

I-Indeterminate           The node is high - Z, and contains an indeterminate
                          value. This is the state leftover after a contention
                          or indeterminate driven state.

A-Indeterminate high      There is an indeterminate amount of drive
                          coming from a driven high node.

B-Indeterminate low       There is an indeterminate amount of drive
                          coming from a driven low node.

D-Weak indet high         There is an indeterminate amount of weak drive
                          coming from a driven low node.

E-Weak indet low          There is an indeterminate amount of weak drive
                          coming from a driven low node.

C-Contention              There are conflicting drives on the node.

F-Weak contention         There are conflicting weak drives on the node.

Defined states: A defined state has a definate voltage value, either vss or
vcc. Again, however, there are many different types, classed into driven
and stored.

1-Driven high             There is a high drive on the node.

0-Driven low              There is a low drive on the node.

H-Stored high             There is a high voltage stored on a high-z node.

L-stored low              There is a low voltage stored on a high-z node.

J-Weak high               There is a high weak drive on the node.

K-Weak low                There is a low weak drive on the node.

P-Vcc                     The node is connected DIRECTLY to the high voltage
                          rail.

G-Vss                     The node is connected DIRECTLY to the low voltage
                          rail.

Combinations: The results of two states meeting in a circuit can be told
according to this state table. There are 256 possible combinations, although
of course some of them are redundant.

              U I A B D E C F 1 0 H L J K P G
             ---------------------------------
           U |U|I|A|B|D|E|C|F|1|0|I|I|J|K|P|G|
           I |I|I|A|B|D|E|C|F|1|0|I|I|J|K|P|G|
           A |A|A|A|C|A|A|C|A|1|C|A|A|A|A|P|G|
           B |B|B|C|B|B|B|C|B|C|0|B|B|B|B|P|G|
           D |D|D|A|B|D|C|C|C|1|0|D|D|J|F|P|G|
           E |E|E|A|B|C|E|C|C|1|0|E|E|F|K|P|G|
           C |C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|C|P|G|
           F |F|F|A|B|C|C|C|F|1|0|F|F|F|F|P|G|
           1 |1|1|1|C|1|1|C|1|1|C|1|1|1|1|P|G|
           0 |0|0|0|0|0|0|C|0|C|0|0|0|0|0|P|G|
           H |I|I|A|B|D|E|C|F|1|0|H|I|J|K|P|G|
           L |I|I|A|B|D|E|C|F|1|0|I|L|J|K|P|G|
           J |J|J|A|B|J|F|C|F|1|0|J|J|J|F|P|G|
           K |K|K|A|B|F|K|C|F|1|0|K|K|F|K|P|G|
           P |P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|P|*|
           G |G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|G|*|G|
             ---------------------------------

The rationale for each of these rules: The states form groups. The groups
are:

     1. Driven - A, B, D, E, C, F, 1, 0, J and K. These are states
        that have one or more transistors supplying current to
        support that state.

     2. Stored - U, I, H, and L. These are states that exist on a
        high-Z node stored in the capacitience of that node.

     3. Strong - A, B, C, 1, 0, P and G. These are states that
        are supplied by strong transistors.

     4. Weak - D, E, F, J and K. These are driven states that are
        supplied by weak transistors.

     5. Driven high - A, D, 1, and 0

The basic rules for the combination of states are:

     1. Any state with itself results the same state.

     1. A strong driven state wins over any weak driven or
        stored state.

     2. A weak driven state wins over any stored state.

     3. Like strength driven states of opposite polarity result
        in contention of the same strengh.

     3. Contention wins over any state of like strength.

     4. Valid driven states win over driven indeterminates
        of like polarity.

     5. Stored states of opposite polarity result in a stored
        indeterminate.

     6. Any stored state with an indeterminate stored state
        result in a stored indeterminate.

Unrealistic rules: There are a few rules that do not result in realistic
circuit behavor. The rules are worst case in that a circuit that might
work in the real world would be flagged bad, but not vice-versa.

     1. Since any strong indeterminate wins over any weak state,
        a weak high or low is not able to combine with a strong
        indetermiate state of like polarity, even though in a real
        circuit a correct high or low would result.
        This rule is nessary as in the following problem:

             An indeterminate strong high state meets a
             weak high state. In simulation this would be
             an indeterminate strong high, but in a real
             circuit would in fact be a valid high.
             The result cannot be considered a strong high
             as the weak component could be overcome.
             Similarly, it cannot be considered a weak high
             as it cannot in fact be overriden by a strong
             low.

        Fortunately, weak drives are used sparingly, and conflicts
        will rarely arise.

              CMOS SIMULATION GENERAL ALGORITHM

We simulate transistors as ideal switches, witth no propagation delay
from source to drain, and "unit" delay from gate to switch. The "nodes"
are N-way connections that are capacitive in that they will hold a given
state until driven otherwise. The nodes are the only circuit elements that
change state as the simulation progresses.
The network as loaded consists of two parts: the transistor list and the
node directory. The transistor list consists of a linear list of transistors,
with arbitrary connections from the source, gate and drain to nodes in the
node directory. The node directory is a listt of entries containing the
name, current and next states, and which transistor is responsible for the
node state (or the last such transistor).
The states for each node include a high, low and indeterminate, which
indicates that a true high or low has not been established. The high and
low states are divided according to whether the node is currently driven
or is a state stored on the node. Stored states are subject to "decay",
which causes the node to assume an indeterminate state after a finite
number of clocks. The decay is an adjustable parameter, and can be made
dependent on the number of attached transistors. This can be adjusted to
realistically model worst case node decay (all attached transistors to the
driven opposite state). The simulation is by "confidence" in that each
driven state is replaced by it's stored equivalent at the start of each
"clock", and the driven state must be re-established.
The indeterminate states break into undefined, indeterminate, indeterminate
driven, and contention. The undefined state is simply a stored
indeterminate, but all nodes are set to it on simulation start so that the
definition of nodes can be watched. The indeterminate state is a stored
value of unknown voltage, and occurs typically as the aftermath of a
contention or other driving state that does not clarify the node state.
A node driven to conflicting states takes the contention state, which will
tend to propagate if unchecked (since it is itself a driven mode state).
Finally, the driven indeterminate is a special state used when an
indeterminate state is driven on a node.
Indeterminate states indicate at least that the possiblity exists of a
non-rail to rail voltage and of static current flow. They serve three
purposes. They can exist briefly while a circuit changes state due to
different delay paths, or may be a normal mode of "trick" circuits
(as pseudo-CMOS), or may indicate real faults in the design. In general,
an indeterminate indicates that more power will be drawn than the CMOS
nature would normally indicate.
The transistor "evaluation" follows three different modes based on the
state of it's gate. For an "off" transistor, no action occurs, as the
transistor represents an ideal open. For "on" and "indeterminate" states,
a lookup is performed by the source and drain states to find the next
source and drain states by the preceeding ones. The reason for indeterminate
evaluation is that the state must be evaluated "critically", so that a
transistor may be assumed to "corrupt" a node but not be able to set a
true driven high or low. Driven indeterminates are created only in this
mode, and the transistor that caused such a state is remembered so that
a promotion to contention state can be correctly evaluated.
Each "clock" cycle starts by setting all modes to stored state and running
through the transistor list evaluating each transistor independently.
Since this can cause propagated states to N nodes, the evaluation run
is repeated until no states change, to "relax" the circuit. Since the
gates stay static through the run, inability to settle should not be
possible. truly astable circuits will manefest over several clock cycles.
The gate unit delay is inherent in the cycle time to process gates.
We allow a "step" factor to convert the gate delays into real time based
on a real world worst case delay factor.

Algorithim advances

A better picture of the true state of a node would be obtained by dividing
driven and stored highs and lows into partial and full states. This would
truly represent the drop caused by a level passed by the wrong type of
transistor, and therefore a departure from true complementary logic. This
would be again for diagnosic reasons and pseudo-CMOS designs.
"winner" modes such as used for pseudo-CMOS ram structures can be modeled
using weak N and P channel transistors. These would behave as normal
transistors save that they would lose to stronger transistors. Alternately,
winners can be determined by transistor sizes included in the net
specification.

Fidelity and realisim of simulation

To some extent, the purpose of a switch level simulation is not to represent
true reality but to define a simplified system whose rules are a logical
subset of reality. The goal is met if the two basic criteria are met:

     1. There are no "valid" modes in the simulation that
        turn to "invalid" modes in reality.

     2. The simulation correctly models circuit constructs in use.

Delay modeling

We model delays by picking the clock relation to real time so that it
represents a quantization based on the worst case system delay. This
is realistic in that the last settling node after, say a clock edge,
represents a worst case estimate of the total net settle time. What is
not realistic is the "order" in which the circuit will settle, and
therefore it is possible to built a circuit that is "valid" under
simulation, but not in real life because it does not follow like settling
order. The difficulties with time representation can be solved by
basing the circuit on a global clock, and syncronizing inputs to this
clock. Then, the designer must also insure that race conditions do not
exist in the design. To this end, the simulation provides a "close"
model of real world delays, as the gate to switch delay of a transistor
indeed represents a much larger value than the delay to move charge
about the circuit.

Voltage modeling

CMOS certainly tries to minimize the effect of voltage approximation
problems. Only using pseudo-CMOS does this effect come back in force. To
this extent, partial level modeling is required to make some such
circuits function in simulation.
The charge decay system provides a worst case check on charge prooblems,
and can accurately imitate decay in the real world.

A model

A good model for discussion is the setting of a inverter ring via an
N-MOS pass transistor:

! Pass transistor

n input control store

! Driver inverter

inv store storeb

! Feedback weak inverter

winv storeb store

Here, the pass transistor can pass a perfect low state, but an imperfect
high or partial high state, and the feedback weak inverter is in a winner
mode with the driver beyond the pass transistor (which we assume is a
strong driver). To set a low store state is done by setting a winner with
the weak inverter. To set a high store state, the store state first
proceeds to a partial high as a result of the win over the weak inverter,
Which will in time propagate to a full high when the weak inverter
changes state.
